            "text": "Integrating ACE-Step 1.5 Turbo into Your API Stack"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "p",
        "children": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Begin by configuring the model endpoint with authentication tokens and rate limiting. Use standard REST or gRPC protocols for seamless integration. Implement health checks and fallback mechanisms to handle model downtime. Ensure your API gateway routes requests efficiently, leveraging load balancers to distribute traffic based on the benchmark's throughput insights."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "h2",
        "children": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Optimizing Performance with ACE-Step 1.5 Turbo"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "p",
        "children": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Tune parameters like batch size and timeout settings based on benchmark data to reduce latency spikes. Monitor metrics in real-time using tools like Prometheus or Grafana, aligning with the benchmark's throughput thresholds. Scale horizontally by adding instances during peak loads, and cache frequent requests to offload model inference. Regularly rerun benchmarks after updates to maintain optimal performance."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "h2",
        "children": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Common Pitfalls and How to Avoid Them"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "p",
        "children": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Avoid misconfiguring resource allocations, which can lead to OOM errors—refer to benchmark resource usage for guidance. Handle API errors gracefully by implementing retries with exponential backoff, especially for transient failures indicated in benchmark stress tests. Ensure data preprocessing aligns with model expectations to prevent accuracy drops, and validate inputs against benchmark test cases to maintain consistency."
